The internal rate of return is a measure of the profitability of a given project. Since it is internal, it does not include the inflation and other external factors such as risk-free rate and capital. 

In order to solve the internal rate of return, we will use the formula for net present value:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{NPV}&=-\text{Initial investment}+\text{net working capital}+\text{present value of cash flow}\\
&+\dfrac{\text{Salvage value}-\text{Capital reduction}}{(1+\text{Internal rate  of return})^\text{time}}
\end{aligned}$$

Simplifying the equation, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\$345,000&=\$356,620+\left(\dfrac{-\$33,400}{(1+\text{IRR})^5}\right)\\[15 pt]
-\$11,620&=\dfrac{-\$33,400}{(1+\text{IRR})^5}
\end{aligned}$$
